ted Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England",", , Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richardson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Richard   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Ritson  .","Americanized form (and a Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Richardsson</b> or <b>Rikardsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Richard  , <i>Rikard</i>.","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish <b>Richardsen</b> or Norwegian <b>Rikardsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Richarson","meanings":["English: variant of   Richardson  ."]},{"name":"Richerson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson   or perhaps a patronymic from   Richer  ."]},{"name":"Richard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Richeson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson  , but compare   Richerson  ."]},{"name":"Ritson","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Richson</b>, a shortened form of   Richardson  . The name may sometimes have been confused with or assimilated to   Rushton  .","in southern England perhaps a habitational name from Ritson, in Halwell (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":69,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Richardson was born in 1500, in England. He married Mrs Richardson about 1535, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1500–":"1500–Surnud","1519–Female":"1519–Surnud","1536–1595":"1536–1595","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1536":"1536","1500":"1500","1595":"1595","Abt 1535":"umbes 1535","1519":"1519","1549":"1549",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England",", , Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1500–":"1500–Kuollut","1519–Female":"1519–Kuollut","1536–1595":"1536–1595","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1536":"1536","1500":"1500","1595":"1595","Abt 1535":"noin 1535","1519":"1519","1549":"1549",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"England",", , Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1500–":"1500–Décédé","1519–Female":"1519–Décédée","1536–1595":"1536–1595","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1536":"1536","1500":"1500","1595":"1595","Abt 1535":"environ 1535","1519":"1519","1549":"1549",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre",", , Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Richardson est né en 1500, à Angleterre. Il a épousé Mrs Richardson environ 1535, à Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il est décédé à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1500–":"1500–Verstorben","1519–Female":"1519–Verstorben","1536–1595":"1536–1595","1500–Male":"1500–Verstorben","1569":"